'''Lagden's bushshrike''' ('''''Malaconotus lagdeni''''') is a [[bird]] [[species]] in the [[bushshrike]] [[Family (taxonomy)|family]] (Malaconotidae) native to Africa. It is a stocky bird with yellow or orange-yellow underparts, olive green upperparts, a grey head and heavy bill. Two subspecies are recognised.

==Taxonomy==
[[Richard Bowdler Sharpe]] described the species in 1884 as ''Laniarius lagdeni'', from a specimen collected in the vicinity of Kumasi in Ghana. However there were no further sightings of the species in this locale for the whole 20th century.<ref name="iucn status 18 November 2021" /> He named it in honour of [[Godfrey Yeatman Lagden|Sir Godfrey Yeatman Lagden]], an English diplomat who served as Chief Clerk to the Secretary of the State of Transvaal and Secretary to Sir [[Owen Lanyon]].{{sfn|Beolens|Watkins|Grayson|2014|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=En4wBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT715 715]}}
[[File:Malaconotus lagdeni - Don Wellmann - 452637717.jpeg|thumb|Live bird]]
There are two disjunct populations, classified as separate subspecies: ''Malaconotus lagdeni lagdeni'', from eastern [[Sierra Leone]], through Liberia, Ivory Coast and southern Ghana to western [[Togo]], and ''Malaconotus lagdeni centralis'', in the [[Albertine Rift montane forests]].{{sfn|Westoll|1998|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=phFFAAAAYAAJ&q=Lagden%27s+bushshrike 464]}} {{sfn|Briggs|Roberts|2013|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=xKwxuUIxtHAC&pg=PA69 68–69,  273, 287, 322]}} The western subspecies has more orange tinge on the underparts while the central African subspecies has none.{{sfn|Harris|2010|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=OqJCKm9adAkC&pg=P212 212]}}{{sfn|Stevenson|Fanshawe|2004|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=jcN1OCKC-bQC&pg=PA476 476]}}

==Description==
Lagden's bushshrike is a stocky bird some 23&nbsp;cm long with a heavy black bill. The adult male and female are similar in plumage. The upper parts, including the wings and tail, are olive-green, and the head is dark grey. The underparts are yellow, sometimes tinged orange on the breast. The tail is edged with yellow. The legs are bluish grey.{{sfn|Harris|2010|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=OqJCKm9adAkC&pg=P212 212]}}<!-- cites para -->

Juveniles have duller plumage overall, with brownish upperparts yellow or white underparts, sometimes with some streaking, and a grey-brown bill.{{sfn|Harris|2010|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=OqJCKm9adAkC&pg=P212 212]}}

It can be distinguished from the [[fiery-breasted bushshrike]] as the latter species has a much redder breast and light grey head.{{sfn|Harris|2010|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=OqJCKm9adAkC&pg=P212 212]}}

The call has been described as a ''hoop hoop'' or a ''toot toot...''.{{sfn|Harris|2010|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=OqJCKm9adAkC&pg=P212 212]}}{{sfn|Borrow|Demey|2013|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=tcwXBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA274 274]}}  Others have said it is a "bell note" call, like the [[grey-headed bushshrike]] but at a higher pitch.{{sfn|Stevenson|Fanshawe|2004|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=jcN1OCKC-bQC&pg=PA476 476]}}  This [[Bird vocalization|avian vocalization]] has been described using the odd consonant-filled word "Chrrrr".{{efn-ua|Which is also designated as a [[camel driver]] command, and the "courting call of a [[Gecko]]."{{sfn|Conley|2009|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=yk1j1WLh80QC&dq=Lagden%27s+bushshrike&pg=PA43 42–43]}}  Still other observers and ornithologists describe the song differently.{{sfn|Borrow|Demey|2013|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=tcwXBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA274 274]}}}} Recordings of the calls exist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://avocet.zoology.msu.edu/recordings/7239 |title=Lagden's Bush-shrike, Malaconotus lagdeni centralis Recording AV#7239. |location=Uganda: [[Bwindi National Park]], Ruhija Gate (−1.07, 29.758) |first1=Ryan |last1=Sucaet |format=Audio |publisher=Avian Vocalizations Center, [[Michigan State University]] |access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://macaulaylibrary.org/browse/taxa/Malaconotus-lagdeni  |title=Malaconotus-lagdeni |publisher=[[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]] [[Macaulay Library]] [[Cornell University]] |access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://macaulaylibrary.org/audio/101965 |first1=Ian |last1=Sinclair |location=Ivory Coast |title=Lagden's Bushshrike – Malaconotus lagdeni |format=Audio |year=1990 |publisher=[[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]] [[Macaulay Library]] [[Cornell University]] |access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref>

Loud flapping ("fripping") of wings commonly associated.{{sfn|Harris|2010|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=OqJCKm9adAkC&pg=P212 212]}}

==Distribution and habitat==
Its natural [[habitat]]s are subtropical or tropical moist lowland [[forest]]s in west Africa to an elevation of around 700 m, and subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]]s in [[Rwanda]], [[Uganda]] and the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] at an elevation of 2100 to 2800 m.{{sfn|Harris|2010|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=OqJCKm9adAkC&pg=P212 212]}} Classified in the [[IUCN Red List]] as ''Near Threatened'', it is becoming rare due to [[habitat loss]].<ref name="iucn status 18 November 2021" />  One of the 1,487 bird species of eastern Africa,{{sfn|van Perlo|2009|page=180}} it is considered to be a "very rare mountain forest species".{{sfn|Williams|Arlott|1988|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=Y3pFAQAAIAAJ&q=Lagden%27s+bushshrike 283]}}   It is one of the 235 different species sighted at [[Kyabobo National Park]].<ref name="IUCN">{{cite book |url=https://portals.iucn.org/library/sites/library/files/documents/2010-073.pdf |pages=16–17 |title=Parks and Reserves of Ghana: Management Effectiveness Assessment of Protected Areas |quote=There are at least 235 different species of birds in Kyabobo. Lagden's bush shrike Malaconotus lagdeni is listed as globally "Near Threatened" and is a new record for Ghana |publisher=[[IUCN]] – International Union for Conservation of Nature |year=2010 |access-date=February 10, 2017}}</ref>

==Feeding==
Lagden's bushshrike hunts large insects, such as grasshoppers, and other arthropods, as well as small vertebrates, foraging in forest canopy 10–30 m (35–100&nbsp;ft) above the ground.{{sfn|Harris|2010|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=OqJCKm9adAkC&pg=P212 212]}}{{sfn|del Hoyo|Elliott|Sargatal|2009|pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=BiZaAAAAYAAJ&q=Lagden%27s+bushshrike 68, 83]}}

